{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528491"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14306"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14306"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.15,0.64,0.21,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7001"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94122"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4353"},{"type":"tags","id":"4354"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45903"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 36+5 weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. This is her first pregnancy, which has been uncomplicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal palpation suggests a breech presentation. An ultrasound confirms a frank breech presentation with adequate amniotic fluid volume. Fetal growth measurements are normal. The placenta is anterior and clear of the cervical os. Cardiotocography shows a reassuring fetal heart rate pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform amniocentesis","Schedule elective caesarean section","Perform external cephalic version","Continue routine antenatal care","Induce labour immediately"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eperform external cephalic version (ECV)\u003C/strong\u003E. ECV is a procedure where the fetus is manually rotated from a breech presentation to a cephalic (head-down) presentation through manipulation of the maternal abdomen. It is recommended for uncomplicated breech pregnancies at 36-37 weeks gestation, which is precisely the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScheduling an elective caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature at this stage. While caesarean section is often performed for breech presentations at term, it is not the first-line management. Attempting ECV first can potentially avoid the need for a caesarean section and its associated risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing routine antenatal care\u003C/strong\u003E without addressing the breech presentation would be inappropriate. The breech presentation at this gestational age requires active management to optimise the chances of a vaginal delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInducing labour immediately\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in a breech presentation. Vaginal breech delivery carries higher risks compared to cephalic presentation, and induction would not be attempted without first trying to turn the baby.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming amniocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this scenario. Amniocentesis is typically used for genetic testing or assessment of fetal lung maturity, neither of which are relevant to managing a breech presentation at term.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EECV has a success rate of about 50% in nulliparous women and is generally safe when performed by experienced practitioners. Contraindications to ECV include placenta praevia, multiple pregnancy, recent vaginal bleeding, and certain fetal or uterine anomalies. None of these contraindications are present in this case. Before and after the procedure, ultrasound should be performed to confirm fetal position and well-being. If ECV is unsuccessful or declined, then planning for either a caesarean section or, in carefully selected cases, a vaginal breech delivery in a facility with appropriate resources and expertise would be the next step.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["External cephalic version (ECV) is recommended for uncomplicated breech pregnancies at 36-37 weeks gestation.","Contraindications to ECV include placenta praevia, multiple pregnancy, and recent vaginal bleeding.","Ultrasound should be performed before and after ECV to confirm fetal position and well-being."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Management of breech presentation at term [Internet]. East Melbourne (Australia): RANZCOG; 2016. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Management-Breech-Presentation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14306"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94122"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-24T13:47:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-24T13:59:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7001"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112056"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1217"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Ultrasound","synonyms":["US","Ultrasonography"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2